"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from Department of Health (PEX 0028)&#xa0;&#xa0;\nContents&#xa0;1              \nNHS EFFICIENCY CHALLENGE1.1\n              \nThe ‘Nicholson Challenge’ in 2012–13\n1.2\n              \nThe challenge in 2013–14 and beyond\n1.3\n              \nDelivering transformational change\n1.4\n              \nThe prospects for the long-term viability of NHS trusts and NHS foundation\n trusts\n2              \nSOCIAL CARE SERVICES2.1\n              \nThe impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 Spending Review\n2.2\n              \nThe impact on NHS plans of decisions currently being made by local authorities\n2.3\n              \nThe ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savings\n2.4\n              \nThe use of additional funding for social care being made available through the NHS budget\n3              \nINTEGRATION OF HEALTH AND CARE SERVICES3.1\n              \nProgress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services\n4              \nFUNDING4.1\n              \nThe effectiveness of the mechanisms by which \nresources are distributed geographically in the NHS\n4.2\n              \nFinancial pressures in the system, such as funding for general practic\ne, and for A&amp;E services.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n1&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNHS EFFICIENCY CHALLENGE&#xa0;\n1.1&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe ‘Nicholson Challenge’ in 2012–13 &#xa0;\n1\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nBy the end of the \n2010\n \nS\npending \nR\neview period (\ncovering \n2011\n–12\n to 2014\n–15\n) the NHS will have received more than £12.\n7\n billion of increased funding, but it will still face significant additional demand for services arising from demographic change, public expectations and pressures to fund new technologies and d\nrugs. To meet this challenge the NHS needs to secure up to £20 billion of efficiency savings by 2014\n–15\n, and will have to keep delivering efficiency savings o\nf a similar scale \nin 2015\n–16\n \nand beyond\n.\nQIPP delivery in 2011–12 and 2012–132\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn the first two ye\nars of the QIPP delivery period, the NHS has delivered in line with its forecast efficiency savings, with \nprimary care trusts (\nPCTs\n)\n reporting delivery of £5.8 billion savings in 2011–12 and a further £5.0 billion in 2012–13.\n3\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWhile this is an encouraging p\nerformance through the first half of the QIPP delivery period, it will require concerted effort across the health system to maintain delivery over the second half of the period in a sustainable way that prepares the NHS for continuing financial challenges \nin 2013–14 and \nbeyond \ndiscussed in section 1.2\n.\n4\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWhile \ndelivering savings of £10.8 billion over two years, the NHS has maintained its strong overall performance on key measures on hospital-acquired infections, ambulance response and overall A&amp;E performance\n.\n Evidence shows\n:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n5\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn response to the \ndiff\niculties \nA&amp;E \nfaced during quarter 4 \nt\nhe Department has \ntaken early action by \nearmarking \n£500\n \nm\nillion\n to \nensure staff have the support they need during the next \ntwo\n \nwinter\ns\n and that patients are not left facing excessive waits for treatment.\n Prof\nessor \nSir B\nruce Keogh \nis \ncarry\ning\n out a review \nof urgent and emergency care l\nook\ning\n at the demands on services and how the NHS should respond in the long term.\n1.2&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe challenge in 2013–14 and beyond6\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNHS staff are improving their productivity: according to Office for National Statistics figures, between \nthe years \n2000 and 2\n010, labour productivity in healthcare rose faster than in the economy as a whole.  In particular, the NHS has responded well to the QIPP challenge. NHS staff across the country are using the opportunity that QIPP provides to improve services.  A few examp\nles of the improvements underway are:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n7\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nQIPP plans for 2013–14 are expected to deliver savings of £4.2 billion. Based on the latest results (August 2013), NHS England expects to deliver £4.0 billion in 2013–14, 5% below the target. This was split between provide\nr productivity savings delivered through the tariff reduction in contracts (£2.2 billion planned) and CCG/direct commissioning (£2.0 billion planned):\n&#xa0;\n8\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe shortfall \nin QIPP impacts on the overall financial performance of NHS England. From an assessment of risks and mitigations for the current financial year, NHS England has identified a continued imbalance of financial risk between individual CCGs and between CCGs and\n direct commissioning, with the direct commissioning financial position being the more fragile. In year the risks have been largely mitigated; however, whil\ne\n the risks arising have a recurrent impact into future years the sources of mitigation are largely non-recurrent.\nDepartmental efficiency plans&#xa0;\n9\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPay restraint is an important part of the Government’s strategy to meet the current economic and fiscal challen\nges while maintaining services and jobs. The Government has set clear expectations on pay restraint across the public services, with public sector pay awards averaging up to 1% in 2013–14 and 2014–15. The 2013 Budget confirmed that public sector pay awards\n in 2015–16 will be limited to an average of up to 1%, and the \n2013 S\npending \nReview\n confirmed the cross-government commitment to reducing the cost of progression pay in public services, including the NHS. In the longer term, of course, pay trends will be d\nependent on wider economic factors.\n10\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEmployers want to secure a better balance between pay, performance and productivity. To deliver \nthe\n aspirations for the prevention of ill\n-\nhealth and the delivery of seven\n-\nday care, national pay frameworks must be fit for\n purpose, fair to staff and offer the taxpayer the very best value for money. The NHS will be in a stronger position to maintain or increase staffing levels, and therefore protect jobs, if employers are able to make better use of their pay bill.\n11\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Govern\nment has \ntherefore invited the NHS Pay Review Body to consider, if they believe an award is justified, how any such award might be made dependent on the partners (NHS Staff Council) reaching agreement on further Agenda for Change (AfC) reform. In particula\nr, how in the current economic climate and within the context of the overall expenditure on pay and pensions, AfC might be made more affordable. \nIt is \nproposed that any such recommendation is tied to progress on AfC reform, with the parties invited to repo\nrt on progress in their evidence to the NHS\n \nP\nay \nR\neview \nB\nody\n next year, effectively deferring any award.\n12\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nHowever, it is recognised that to meet the efficiency challenge the NHS needs to deliver recurrent efficiency savings of up to £20 billion by 2014–15. T\nhis means that any one-off savings will need to be replaced with other sources of savings in subsequent years. The National Audit Office has confirmed that the vast majority (over 90%) of efficiency savings delivered to date are recurrent\n.\n13\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn the reformed\n health system, all organisations will have a role to play in driving the required efficiency improvements, with NHS England having a particularly crucial responsibility. Ensuring the delivery of QIPP was built into NHS England’s authorisation and planning\n processes for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs).\n14\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe strong NHS QIPP performance since 2011–12, which is continuing into 2013–14, gives a firm foundation for sustained delivery over the rest of this Spending Review period, against a backdrop of on-goin\ng challenges from rising demands for NHS services\n.\n15\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Department is also taking action centrally to support the NHS to deliver the sustained savings that are needed.\n16\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn August 2013,  the Department published its strategy for holding NHS spending on non-pa\ny items flat over the next three years\n, which w\nould \nsee procurement and agency spend across the NHS reduced by £1.5 billion in real terms by the end of 2015–16\n, t\nhus helping the NHS meet both the current QIPP challenge and the efficiency challenge in 2015\n–16 and beyond.\nThe financial challenge17\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe 2010 \nSpending Review set the NHS a challenge to deliver up to £20\n \nb\nillion\n of annual efficiency savings by 2014\n–15\n. The budgets announced in the \ns\npending \nr\nound in July \n2013 \nmake clear that the financial challeng\ne will be even greater in 2015\n–16\n.\n Given the financial situation, more efficiencies will be needed in future years: \nin \nsummer\n 2013\n, NHS England published its Call to Action\n, which estimated that the NHS would need to make £30\n \nb\nillio\nn of savings between \n2014\n–15\n and 2020\n–21\n. This extended period of significant savings requirements has important consequences for the need to embrace transformational change to secure sustainability.\nImproving outcomes for patients18\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEven within this challenging efficiency req\nuirement, NHS England is determined to place improving outcomes for patients at the heart of their work, and to do its part in meeting the challenges which have been laid out by the Francis, Keogh and Berwick reviews of the NHS. For that reason, commission\ners are expected to prioritise an approach to planning which combines transparency with detailed patient and public participation. \nThere n\need to \nbe\n, from the bottom up, quantifiable ambitions for each domain\n of the NHS Outcomes Framework.\n19\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNHS England will \ntherefore be asking CCGs and Area Teams to work together to determine local levels of ambition, based on evidence of local patient and public benefit, against a common set of indicators that place \nthe\n duty to tackle health inequalities front and centre sta\nge. This will ensure that the improvements \nNHS England is \naiming to deliver for patients\n,\n across \neight\n key areas\n, are clearly articulated:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe need for transformational change20\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNHS England is continuing to focus attention on the QIPP challenge in order to maintain or improve the quality of healthcare services in a c\nonstrained funding \nenvironment.\n21\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAs the previous section shows, QIPP has so far not met its targets for transformational change, which is vital for the financial sustainability of the NHS in the long term. QIPP savings so far have been weighted towards central actions, includ\ning pay and administrative cost reductions and tactical efficiency programmes. The NHS cannot rely on pay restraint and reductions in the unit cost of care to deliver QIPP-scale efficiencies in the\n long term.\n22\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo address this, NHS England has increased the \nsystem’s focus on transformational change.  From 2013\n–14\n onwards, QIPP plans for CCGs and NHS England’s direct commissioners are broken down between transactional schemes (where savings are expected to be achieved through productivity \nand contractual savin\ngs) and transformational schemes such as service re-design and pathway changes. In 2013\n–14\n, the transformational schemes represent 44% of the total QIPP target for CCGs and direct commissioners (£0.9 billion). The latest data (from August) shows that £0.2 \nbillion (22% of the planned savings) had already been delivered and NHS England forecasts that £0.7 billion (78% of the planned savings) will be achieved by the end of the year. The shortfall on transformational schemes account for the vast majority of the\n total forecast QIPP shortfall. QIPP performance is measured against phased plans on a monthly basis as part of t\nhe NHS England finance report.\n23\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDoing\n better on procurement, productivity and transforming care pathways\n is a must\n.  \nI\nmproving procurement will \nbe a vital contribution to sustainable efficiency savings.  The Department of Health announced a new strategy for NHS procurement in August\n 2013 (see footnote \n2\n)\n.\n24\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nImprovements in workforce productivity are key to helping deliver the efficiency savings in t\nhis, and the next, spending round period. So far, workforce productivity gains have contributed 12% of the total savings made in 2011–12 and 2012–13, compared with 23% which has come from pay restraint. The workforce productivity share of total savings is \nexpected to grow to 26% in 2013–14 and 2014–15. Despite improved productivity performance in the last two years, there still exists wide labour productivity variation at provider level. Levelling up performance as well as shifting the average provider perf\normance upwards will help achieve the workforce produ\nctivity gains that are needed.\n25\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWhere activity has fallen so far, this is more due to contractual levers than to changing the way \nthe NHS\n deliver\ns\n care. To turn this increased productivity into savings, p\nroviders as well as processes\n will need to transform\n, moving more care out of hospitals.  \nT\nransform\ning\n the way in which health and social care services are delivered, using available resources more effectively and focusing on integrated care and prevention\n to improve patient outcomes and experience\n is required\n.\n26\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Department and NHS England have a key role to play in setting out and driving the case for transformational change. For example, the Secretary of State has challenged the NHS to go ‘paperless’ by\n 2018, highlighting the potential benefits for patients and for taxpayers. The Mandate to NHS England set objectives for it to lead the health and care system in driving better integration of services; and the Government will hold NHS England to account fo\nr its performance. However, this transformation cannot be imposed from the top. Engagement on specific local service changes needs to be locally led, and it is CCGs and their local partners that are best placed to understand the needs of their communities \nand the\n opportunities for improvement.\n27\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIt is vital for organisations to work collaboratively to communicate the case for transformational change and to deliver it: both to benefit patients and to improve efficiency. Continued protection of health funding d\noes not mean that all services should remain unchanged. The NHS must adapt and evolve \nto meet the challenges of future demographic trends a\nnd rising demand expectations.\n28\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Government’s modernisation of the NHS will enable commissioners to make changes th\nat will deliver real improvements in quality through commissioning that is driven by clinical insight, patient choice and a focus on improving outcomes. This will promote greater integration of services at the local level, including a more coordinated appr\noach to assessment, care planning and care management. Together with increased patient choice and a more rigorous and transparent system for regulating providers, this modernisation will provide much stronger incentives and opportunities to deliver more in\ntegrated, personalised and preventive care.\n1.3&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDelivering transformational change29\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFrom 1 April 2013, NHS England and C\nCGs \nare responsible for planning and commissioning health services in England. \nD\niagram\n \n1\n \ndescribes \nNHS England’s high-level plan to deliver \nthe \ntransformational change\n necessary for financial stability while improving outcomes for patients.\n&#xa0;\nDiagram\n \n1\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nA national debate&#xa0;\n30\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nRecognising the need for transformational change, NHS England has published \nits Call to Action setting \nout the scale of the challenge facing the NHS through to 2020\n–21,\n and creat\ning\n the basis for a national debate involving the public, charities, NHS staff\n and experts on the future shape of the NHS. NHS England will support CCGs in responding to this debate whil\ne\n also drawing on its conclusions to form \nits \nstrategy for the next ten years.\n31\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNHS England is also working with partner organisations including Moni\ntor, the NHS Trust Development Authority\n (TDA)\n, the L\nocal Government Association (L\nGA\n)\n and others to understand the implications of this challenge across local health and care systems.\n \nSupporting commissioners32\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nCCGs and NHS England’s direct commissioners\n are best placed to identify the opportunities for transforming services.  NHS England is taking steps to\n support their work, including:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n33\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMore broadly, developing, supporting and assuring the commissio\nning system is one of the core processes set out in the NHS England’s business plan. NHS England is committed to provide relevant and sufficient development support for each CCG to enable them to become excellent commissioners and equip them to meet the lo\ncal and national ambitions for service improvement.  The CCG Development Framework was approved in July 2013.\n34\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIt was acknowledged within the framework that greater understanding of what makes a ‘great CCG’ was needed.  A series of different research and in\nsight pieces have been commissioned, which include research into challenges to transformation; a review of international evidence; discussions with leading experts; and gathering and reviewing emerging best practice from CCGs themselves.  NHS England will \npublish the findings from this work \nin\n autumn \n2013 \nas a \nFramework of Excellence in Clinical Commissioning\n. The framework will take the criteria tested during authorisation and puts them within the context of the wider research. CCGs are now considering the\nir development needs in the context of their capacity and capability to meet their local strategic plans for service improvement.\nKey challenges35\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn order to achieve transformational change while delivering efficiencies, new community services can only be\n funded by removing capacity from existing services.  It is vital that the NHS at all levels wins support from partners and t\nhe community for these changes.\n36\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAs part of \nthe \ncollective work on the Call for Action, \nNHS England is \nlooking at how \nit\n can reform \nthe pricing and contracting systems to support transformational change. Starting from 1 April 2014 \nNHS England \nha\ns\n agreed with Monitor that the rules around variation to the national tariff are changed so that localities with ideas that can transform servi\nces for patients are not held back from doing so because of tariff constraints. Together with Monitor, \nit is \nalso committed to publishing further thinking on what this could look like for 2015\n–16 b\ny the end of \n2013.\nIntegration Transformation Fund&#xa0;\n37\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe financial settlement for \n20\n15\n–16\n includes the creation of an \nI\nntegration \nT\nransformation \nF\nund (ITF). This will see the establishment of a pooled budget of £3.8\n \nb\nillion\n, which will be committed at local level with the agreement of \nh\nealth \nand\n \nw\nellbeing \nb\no\nards. Locally, CCGs can decide to place additional resources into the ITF if they wish. The ITF is a ‘game changer’: it creates a substantial ring-fenced budget for investment in out-of-hospital care. However, it will also require the NHS to make savings o\nf over £2\n \nb\nillio\nn in existing spending predominantly relating to acute care. This implies the need for an extra productivity gain of \nbetween \n2\n%\n \nand\n \n3% across the NHS as a whole in \n20\n15\n–16\n, including any immediate ‘dividend’ from investments made under the \nITF itself. NHS England will work with Monitor to determine how this is reflected in the expectations placed on commissioners (in the form of QIPP savings from demand management, pathway change, etc\n.\n) and providers (in the form of the efficiency deflator i\nncorporated in tariff). NHS England is currently exploring the feasibility of bringing forward an element of the \n20\n15\n–16\n saving requirement into \n20\n14\n–15\n to avoid a financial ‘cliff edge’ \nin 2015–16\n.\n38\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe NHS will only be sustainable in \n20\n15\n–16 \nif the ITF \nis\n put \nto the best possible use \nand \nreduce\ns\n significantly the demand for hospital services.  That investment could be targeted at a range of initiatives to develop out\n-\nof\n-\nhospital care, including early intervention, admission avoidance and early hospital dis\ncharge - taking advantage, for example, of new collaborative technologies to give patients more control of their care and transform the cost effectiveness of local services. This will require investment in social care and other \nl\nocal \na\nuthority services, pr\nimary care services and community health services. Crucially, to access the ITF, \nh\nealth and \nw\nellbeing \nb\noards will need to agree a joint plan to transform services, taking account of the impact that plan will have on local NHS services and providers.\n39\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nA critical ingredient of success for the transformation fund will be the quality of partnership working at local level. Health \nand\n \nw\nellbeing \nb\noards will need to have strong governance arrangements for making transparent and evidence-based decisions about t\nhe use of the ITF. The Chief Executive of NHS England will remain the accounting officer for the ITF, accountable to \nP\narliament for its use, and in that context NHS England Area Directors will take a close interest in the effectiveness of local arrangement\ns for governance and implementation.\n1.4&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe prospects for the long-term viability of NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts40\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nOver £60\n \nb\nillio\nn of the \nDepartment’s \nDEL (\nDepartmental Expenditure Limit\n)\n is spent \nvia NHS commissioners \nwith NHS providers \nto \nprovi\nde\n healthcare \nto the public\n. If NHS \np\nrovider expenditure is more than this income, plus income from other sources, then this scores as a cost to the DEL\n,\n and if it is less it is a benefit.\n41\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe capital expenditure of NHS \np\nroviders\n, either financed through their cash surpluses or borrowing, also scores to the DEL.\n42\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNHS \np\nrovider surpluses and deficits\n,\n and capital expenditure score to the DEL in the year that they occur. \nThe Department\n has to include a forecast of th\nese in its own fin\nancial plans.\nRole of the Department43\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Department\n has taken the responsibility for funding the immediate deficit support needs of NHS trusts and NHS \nfoundation trusts (F\nTs\n)\n. However\n,\n the \nD\nepartment is clear that this funding will not be provided on an \nindefinite basis. The role of the \nD\nepartment in providing this support is therefore to drive the development of permanent solutions to financial deficits by ensuring that trusts work with commission\ner\ns and the relevant regulators to develop timely, sustain\nable solutions.\n44\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn the short term, financial support provided by the \nD\nepartment will increase to support the individual deficits of \nNHS \nt\nrusts and FT\ns\n. To provide the necessary challenge back to these organisations, the \nD\nepartment is \npu\ntting mechanisms \nin place \nwhereby access to deficit support is contingent on swift progress to develop sustainable solutions.\n45\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn the first \ninstance\n this will rely on the relevant regulators (TDA and Monitor) to drive the development of sustainable solutions and set clear t\nerms and milestones aro\nund the plans to develop these.\nNHS trusts and the role of TDA&#xa0;\n46\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThere has been a significant shift in the overall financial position of the NHS trust sector. In \n20\n12\n–13,\n \nt\nhe NHS \nt\nrust sector aggregate position was a net £106 million\n surplus\n:\n with 97 out of 102 \nt\nrusts report\ning\n a surplus or breakeven. As at month 4 of \n20\n13\n–14\n, \nthe \nTDA ha\ns\n identified an aggregate forecast outturn deficit of £167 million\n:\n with 31 \nt\nrusts now forecasting an operating deficit at year end.\n47\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe cause of this\n deterioration has been put down to a combination of\n:\n a net price deflator\n;\n a reduction in education and training funding\n; and,\n a commissioner rules-based approach resulting in a decrease in non\n-\nrecurring income from 2012\n–13\n. Further analysis by \nthe \nTDA ha\ns estimated the reduction in non-recurring income to NHS trusts \nas\n £281 million in 2013\n–14\n.\n48\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNon-recurring funding previously provided by \nstrategic health authorities (\nSHAs\n)\n and \nprimary care trusts (\nPCTs\n)\n often supported financial difficulties in trusts. As\n a result\n,\n the change in the outturn position is large\nly\n due to increased transparency revealing the true underlying position of some organisations rather than a sudden worsening of the sustainability of organisations.\n This also means that NHS trusts and F\nTs are treated in the same way.\n49\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe \nTDA is charged with focusing on the organisations struggling to manage their finances. In most cases, the organisations in deficit are the same bodies which face financial challenges to become viable and meet the requirements \nto achieve FT status. The incr\neased transparency of finances presents a new opportunity to understand the underlying causes of these pressures which may \nhave been previously concealed.\n50\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe \nTDA is responsible for developing plans not only to overcome deficits but to take organisations t\no a point where they can integrated into \nthe\n FT land\nscape.\n51\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nOne of the key functions of the TDA is to support the transition of the remaining 99 NHS \nt\nrusts to FT status or to a\nn alternative sustainable form.\n52\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Government wants NHS trusts to improve the qu\nality and sustainability of services as quickly as possible. It is vital that the focus on improving quality cannot be compromised by a focus on the pursuit of \nFT\n status for its own sake. So where time is needed to make the necessary improvement, it is imp\nortant that the process is not rushed and that risks to patient care are not created.\n53\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe 2014 deadline for reaching \nFT\n status has done much to galvanise the NHS trust sector and drive improvement. However, in light of Robert Francis’ report, \nthe Departmen\nt\n ha\ns\n allowed the TDA to agree trajectories for NHS trusts to reach \nFT \nstatus or be \nmoved\n to an alternative\n, more\n sustainable form, on timescales that go beyond 2014\n,\n on a case by case basis. In so doing, \nthis\n will ensure that the primary focus of the TDA \nand of NHS trusts themselves is on improving the quality and sustainab\nility \nof services for patients\n.\nNHS foundation trusts and the role of Monitor54\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAs reported by Monitor \nfor\n \nq\nuarter \n1, 2013–14\n, it is too early to draw firm conclusions on the \nFT \nsector’s performance. However, as at \nq\nuarter \n1\n, the sector net surplus was £27 million, \nthat is \n£9 million higher than planned. Although most FTs \nare\n deliver\ning\n breakeven or better, \none-\nthird \nare\n report\ning\n deficits.\n55\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe FT sector has seen an increase in th\ne number of organisation\ns\n requesting support but not of the level seen in the trust sector as, following authorisation, FTs did not have common access to non-recurrent funding from PCTs and SHAs. This more marginal shift is more likely to be \nas \na result of\n increasing pressure on resources\n, which\n is \nmore \nlikely to be concealed within the larger shifts in the NHS trust sector\n.\nPFI schemes and NHS provider sustainability&#xa0;\n56\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSeven providers \nhave been identified as \nbeing \neligible for funding support totall\ning\n £1.5\n billion over the remaining life of the\nir PFI\n contracts\n to address the contract’s affordability\n. These organisations were \nidentified \nfollowing a wider review of those trusts where affordability of PFI schemes was considered as preventing them from achievin\ng financial sustainability. The \nseven \nproviders \nare:\n57\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nT\nhe wider review also concluded that for \neach of \nthe \nNHS\n trusts, PFI was not the only issue affecting the financial viability and, for most, additional measure\ns within their control or within the control of local health economies would need to be enacted before financial sustainability could be restored.\n58\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe funding for all these organisations will only be made available subject to each organisation meeting the \nfollowing four tests\n:\n59\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAssessm\nent work remains on-going for six organisations. However, for South London Healthcare NHS Trust, a \nsettlement figure was agreed as part of the financial resolutions and agreements for the \nt\nrust being dissolved on 1 October 2013 (following the recommendatio\nns of the Trust Special Administrator appointed in July 2012 under the Regime for Unsustainable NHS Providers). \nThe agreed funding will be paid over the lifetimes of the eligible PFI schemes\n.\n60\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Government has confirmed it remains committed to Public Private Partnerships (PPP) continuing to play an important role in delivering Britain’s future infrastructure. \nHowever, given the problems that some trusts have experienced in affording their PFI \nschemes, the NHS is now proceeding with just a small number of schemes, that \nthe \nDepartment \nhad \napproved to proceed some time ago, under the old PFI model. The Department is however applying new stricter tests to these schemes, particularly with regard to \ndemonstrating\n \naffordability\n.\n61\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAfter extensive consultations, the Government has announced details of a new Public Private Partnership model to replace the PFI, called Private Finance 2 (PF2)\n.\n62\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPF2 contains a number of improvements, compared \nwith\n the previou\ns PFI modelling including:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n63\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe first NHS sche\nme to express interest in adopting the new PF2 model is the £325 million proposal for Sandwell and West Birmingham NHS Trust.\n2&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSOCIAL CARE SERVICES2.1&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 Spending Review64\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPubl\nic finances are in a precarious position. \nTo he\nlp bring\n \nthe deficit under control, local government must \ncontribute \nits share of the savings.\n65\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nBut social care is a key priority for this Government. This is why, against the context of tough public sector fin\nances, \nsteps \nhave\n been\n taken to protect social care services. Over the current \n2010 \nS\npending \nR\neview\n \nperiod significant additional funding \nis being allocated \nto local authorities, including a transfer from the NHS worth £1.1\n \nb\nillio\nn a year by 2014\n–15\n, to be\n spent on social care with a health benefit.\n66\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nS\npending on social care\n, however,\n is ultimately a local decision and some \nlocal authorities \nhave reduced their social care budgets – although there is a lot of local variation. The latest expenditure data shows \nthat total spending in England on adult social care fell by around £200\n \nm\nillion\n in \n20\n12\n–13\n. But budget data published by \nthe Department for Communities and Local Government\n shows that \nlocal authorities \nexpect this to rise again in \n20\n13\n–14\n.\n67\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe latest \nAssociation of Directors of Adult Social Services (\nADASS\n)\n budget survey reports that \nlocal authorities \nhave made significant savings to meet increasing demand, \nand \nthat the vast majority of these savings have come from efficiency gains rather than service \ncuts.\n&#xa0;\n2.2&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe impact on NHS plans of decisions currently being made by local authorities68\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Government \nknow\ns\n that health and social care services are inter-dependent. If one service is operating well \nthen \nit helps the other, while if one is failing t\nhen the other will also suffer.\n69\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThis is why \nsteps \nhave \nbeen \ntaken in recent years to encourage better joint working between the services. In the 2010 S\npending \nR\neview\n \nthe Department \nintroduced a transfer from the NHS to social care, to be used on social \ncare with a health benefit, and gave the NHS up to £300\n \nm\nillion\n a year to deliver reablement services.\n70\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAnd for \n20\n15\n–16\n \nthe Department \nis \ngoing much further by introducing a £3.8\n \nb\nillio\nn pooled budget for health and social care. This will break new ground i\nn driving closer integration, by bring CCGs and local authorities together to make real spending decisions and consider the impact on all services.\n71\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAlthough some \nlocal authorities \nhave reduced their expenditure on adult social care, there is no \nconclusive \nevidence that this is having an impact on the NHS. In fact, \na\n \nkey \nindicator \nthe Department monitors \nsays the opposite: the number of delayed transfers attributed to social care has been falling.\n However, CCGs are (as of August 2013) forecasting an overspen\nd of £40 million on NHS continuing healthcare in 2013–14, which may indicate that social care pressures are having \nsome\n knock-on impact on the NHS.\n2.3&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savings72\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn \nboth \nthe 2010 \nand 2013 \nSpending Review\ns,\n \nthe Department \nworked with ADASS and the \nLocal Government Association (\nLGA\n)\n to establish a realistic assumption for the level of efficiency savings that councils could make. They told us that 3% was a fair assumption, so\n this is the level of efficiency built into the S\npending \nR\neview\n calculations up to \n20\n15\n–16\n.\n73\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe ADASS budget survey reports that \nlocal authorities \nare in fact delivering more than this, achieving around 5% efficiency each year. The survey reports that \nbetter procurement and an increased focus on prevention are the most important ways in which councils are making savings.\n Furthermore t\nhere are two sector-led efficiency programmes that will support \nlocal authorities \nover the next few years to help them to\n do this.\n74\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe LGA’s Adult Social Care Efficiency \np\nrogramme is working with 57 local\n \nauthorities to develop evidence on how to deliver savings in adult social care for the benefit of all local authorities. Projects within the programme cover a range of them\nes including:\n75\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn addition to this p\nrogramme, the Towards Excellence in Adult Social Care programme has produced a toolkit to aid local authorities in identifying areas where they could make efficiencies.\n2.4&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe use of additional funding for social care being made available through the NHS budget76\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nI\nn 2012\n–13\n, \nsome \n27% of the \nNHS-funded \ntransfer was used to deliver reablement services – the largest use of the money. A full breakdown of how the money was used in the \nfirst \ntwo years is given in the table \n1\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nTable \n1\n: \nCategory of spend\n2011/12\n%\n2012/13\n%\nCommunity equipment and adaptations\n£32m\n5%\n£25m\n4%\nTelecare\n£29m\n4%\n£19m\n3%\nIntegrated crisis and rapid response services\n£51m\n8%\n£43m\n7%\nMaintaining eligibility criteria\n£116m\n18%\n£74m\n12%\nRe-ablement services\n£117m\n18%\n£168m\n27%\nBed-based intermediate care services\n£61m\n10%\n£34m\n6%\nEarly supported hospital discharge schemes\n£51m\n8%\n£41m\n7%\nMental health services\n£31m\n5%\n£30m\n5%\nOther preventative services\n£67m\n10%\n£45m\n7%\nOther\n£87m\n14%\n£145m\n23%\nTotal£642m&#xa0;£625m&#xa0;&#xa0;\n77\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFrom \n20\n15\n–16\n the introduction of the £3.8 billion ITF pooled budget \nwill provide much needed funding for \nlocal integrated services, including social care\n. T\no access this funding, all areas will need to produce local plans, signed off by \nthe NHS and local authorities, for how the money will be used across health and social care.\n78\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThese plans will need to meet certain conditions, including:\n&#xa0;\n79\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSome \n£1\n \nb\nillio\nn of this money will be linked to outcomes achieved, to create the right incentives to drive the improvements that \nare \nneed\ned\n to meet the challenges facing the health and care system.\n80\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFurther details of how the ITF will work will be published by the end of \n2013\n,\n \nand local areas will agree two-year joint plans in early 2014\n in parallel with the wider joint planning process outlined in section 1.3.\n3&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nINTEGRATION OF HEALTH AND CARE SERVICES3.1&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nProgress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services81\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAcross health and care provision, services are often disjointed and poorly coordinated which causes distress for people who need care a\nnd support as well as their families and carers. Disjointed care leads to poor experiences, worse outcomes and inefficiencies across the system. In contrast, better coordinated care, focused on individuals rather than traditional service boundaries, has th\ne potential to improve services with positive impact on people’s experience, outcomes and on the efficiency of services.\n82\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nHowever, while there is broad consensus that integration has the potential to deliver large benefits, evidence as to the effectiveness \nof specific schemes that the NHS and/or local authorities have put in place is, on the whole, weak. In this context, a policy of top-down reorganisation of services to fit a particular model of integrated care would be counter-productive. This is why the D\nepartment is committed to supporting health and social care organisations to work together to develop local models of integrated care that work for them, by removing barriers, sharing tools and innovations, and helping to build the evidence base of what wo\nrks locally.\n83\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Government has a range of policies to support local integration:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n84\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThese policies have created an environment that supports local innovation and cooperation, but the Government agrees with the Health Select Committee that more needs to be done to \ndrive a real step change in the integration of health and care services.\n85\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThis is why, as part of this year’s spending round, the Government announced \nthe establishment of the Integration Transformation Fund (ITF) \nin 2015–16. The ITF breaks new ground in dr\niving local integration by ensuring that at least £3.8\n \nb\nillio\nn is placed into locally controlled pooled budgets, for use across the health and social care system.\n86\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo ensure that this money is spent in a truly integrated way, it will only be released to are\nas that have jointly agreed plans, signed off by the CCG and the local authority, for how the funding will be used. These plans will reflect a local approach to integrated care, but must also contain some key enablers that we believe are essential, includi\nng:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n87\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe planning process will \nfor the first time bring commissioners from health and social care together to make real decisions about priorities and spending across organisational boundaries. This will have benefits beyond the ITF itself, as plans for this fund will need to be made in\n parallel to, and aligned with, plans for spending the rest of the social care and health budgets. More than ever before, commissioners on both sides will need to be aware of the whole health and social care system. Local authorities and CCGs will also be \nfree to add further money into the pooled budget beyond their share of the £3.8\n \nb\nillio\nn.\n88\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nA \n£1b\nillio\nn \nportion \nof the ITF money will be linked to performance against agreed outcome goals, which could include things like reducing delayed transfers of care or \nimproving patient experience. This will create shared incentives for improvement and require local partners to work closely together to focus on the outcomes that they are seeking\n.\n89\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Department is working with NHS England, the LGA and colleagues from acr\noss central government to finalise the details of how the ITF will work in practice. Detailed guidance for CCGs and \nl\nocal \na\nuthorities, and details of how the funding will be allocated, will be published later \nin 2013 \nalongside NHS planning guidance and the\n local government settlement.\n90\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAll areas will then need to agree plans early next year for how the fund will be used. These plans will cover two years, with 2014\n–15\n used to prepare for the introduction of the pooled budgets and make early progress on priori\nties. To ensure that social care services have the resources to do this, \nas additional £200 million \nha\ns\n \nbeen \nannounced \nfor \ntransfer from the NHS to local authorities in 2014\n–15\n for social care with a health benefit.\n91\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSome of these changes will require legis\nlation and \nthe Department is \n seek\ning\n to make the necessary provisions through the Care Bill.\n4&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFUNDING4.1&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe effectiveness of the mechanisms by which resources are distributed geographically in the NHS92\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe 2012 Health and Social Care Act establishes a new financial landscape with key financial decisions and monitoring to take place \nvariously \nin the Department, NHS England, Monitor and the\n \nTDA. These organisations need to work together to ensure that the \nbest outcomes are \nconsistently \ndelivered for patients and the public whil\ne\n securing value for money and \nremaining within the total Department of Health \nDEL\n provided by HM Treasury.\n93\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn order to achieve this a \nS\nhared \nFinancial Planning Agreement board \n has b\neen established between the key organisations in the new system.  The key underlying principle is that each organisation remains responsible and accountable for financial decisions as set out in the Act but in addition will work together to establish a com\nmon agreement over the \nkey \nfinancial parameters that form the foundation of each organisation’s financial planning.\n94\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThis co-operation is intended to achieve a number of objectives:\n95\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn order to deliver these\n objectives:\n&#xa0;\n96\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAgreement on the key financial parameters will need t\no be reached ahead of the start of each financial year.  The usual planning cycle is that this would be done by the end of each calendar year.\n97\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe final decision on the overall disposition of funding between \nc\nommissioners (NHS England), other \na\nrm\n’\ns\n-l\nength \nb\nodies and \nthat \nheld centrally is made by the Secretary of State, informed by recommendations of the Shared Finan\ncial Planning Agreement \nb\noard.\n98\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nChart \n1\n illustrates the flow of revenue resource funds in 2013–14, extrapolated from the actual flow of funds in\n 2012–13.  The chart figures are illustrative and are based on the planned allocations and forecasts of the sectors within the Department of Health group for 2013–14. The level of funds flows or intra group trading for 2013–14 between the different sectors\n within the group has been estimated, based on 2012–13 data. They are intended to illustrate how the financial transfers within the group work; they are not and are not intended to be a projection of the actual financial performance in 2013–14.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nChart \n1\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n99\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nT\nhe bulk of \nrevenue resource \nfunding is allocated to NHS England\n:\n no funding is \na\nllocated direct to the provider sector.  Instead, the provider sector receives all \nrevenue \nfunding through their trading a\nrr\nangements.\n&#xa0;\nNHS England’s allocations to CCGs&#xa0;\n100\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe 2012 Act that created NHS England also makes it independently responsible for allocating the budgets for commissioning NHS services. This was done to prevent any perception of political interference in the\n way that money is distributed between different parts of the country, although the Mandate can set out the high level aims for the allocation process.  The current mandate, for instance, requires the allocation of resources to have regard to equal access \nfor equal need, draw on independent advice and take account of the importance of stable funding.  Allocation decisions also need to be consistent with NHS England’s legal duties, in particular to have regard to equality of access to and outcomes from healt\nhcare.\n101\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAssessing the effectiveness of allocation decisions is challenging. For instance, it is difficult to isolate the marginal effect of more or less funding on outcomes.  Also, managers strive to manage to their allocations, meaning that the allocations\n are only one factor in determining the financ\nial health of an organisation.\n102\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe design of the process for reaching decisions is therefore critical in delivering a financial allocation that is as effective as possible.  NHS England has adopted an allocatio\nn process that has clear objectives, uses the best independent advice and places reliance on evidence-based approaches complemented by judgement where appropriate.  These are all features that have been preserved from the previous PCT allocation process an\nd which the Public Accounts Committee supported during their landscape review of allocations process across the public sector.\n103\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAt their December 2012 meeting the NHS England board expressed concerns that the proposed target formula for the allocation of re\nsources to CCGs, developed in partnership with the Advisory Committee on Resource Allocation\n (ACRA)\n , if implemented alone, would have led to a greater targeting of resources towards areas with better health outcomes, although in practice this would have b\neen mitigated by pace-of-change decisions. They therefore decided to give each CCG the same growth in programme funding for 2013\n–14\n, giving time to review further the appro\nach to allocation of resources.\n104\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAt the same time NHS England announced a Fundamental\n Review of Allocations, with initial findings being available to influence the approach for 2014\n–15\n.  This covers the local allocation of resources across the full range of NHS England responsibilities, including both allocations to CCGs and the budgets av\nailable for direct commissioning functions.\n105\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe \nr\neview undertook to develop the underlying philosophy for the high\n-\nlevel split between commissioning streams and the linkages between them, including, as part of its longer term objectives, an understanding o\nf the impact of spending on outcomes.\n106\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe key aim of the formula is equal access for equal need. The formulae must facilitate a ‘fair share’ distribution of resources across the country in proportion to need. In addition, NHS England must ensure that the a\nllocation of funding does not cause any destabilising effect on local health economies.\n107\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nLocal allocations are based around four key decisions:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n108\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWith respect to the CCG fair-shares formula (covering £63.4\n \nb\nillio\nn or 66% of NHS England Mandate funding in 2013\n–14\n), a detailed review of the performance of the formula has been undertaken with recommendations as to whet\nher the aims of the formula require amendment to reflect NHS England’s strategies for outcome improvement and inequality reduction, and if so, how this can be achieved in an evidence-based manner.\n109\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn determining need, the formula applies a person-based app\nroach, taking in to account:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n110\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe approach proposed by ACRA is based on current u\ntilisation of services: due to data constraints, this is based on hospital utilisation data rather than health services more broadly.  This is then adjusted for factors that affect utilisation, but are not linked to need, such as proximity to a provider.  \nHowever, this still leaves a possible gap in estimating need where need is systematically unmet.  This is recognised as one of the key challenges for a utilisation based model.\n111\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPrior to 2013\n–14\n, a further adjustment for health inequalities and unmet need w\nas applied to the PCT allocations formula to redistribute 10% of total funding based on the \nd\nisability\n-f\nree \nl\nife \ne\nxpectancy (DFLE),  the number of years someone might expect to live without a long term\n,\n limiting illness. ACRA  has recommended that any adju\nstment for unmet need should be based on the standardised mortality ratio for those under 75 years (SMR&lt;75), which indicates how many more or fewer deaths there are in each area compared with the national average after allowing the different age structures\n in each area. ACRA regards SMR&lt;75 as a significantly more robust metric to use for this purpose, and this would bring the approach to CCG allocations in line with that used in public health. A judgement is required as to whether such an adjustment is appr\nopriate and, if so, what quantum to apply, and options on the inclusion of an adjustment based on SMR&lt;75 are to be put to the NHS England \nb\noard.\n112\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn August 2013, NHS England published initial estimates of the ‘target’ allocations for CCGs based on the ACRA \nrecommendations, to support engagement with NHS, \nl\nocal \na\nuthority colleagues, and other stakeholders. This publication reflected the original formula and current spending estimates considered at the board in December 2012, and did not include any of the fur\nther adjustments for unmet need or inequalities that are currently being considered.  Four regional workshops were held to gather views and inform robust decisions on resource allocation.\n113\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nOne of the key aims of the workshops was to inform judgements NHS En\ngland will have to make around pace-of-change: what the most appropriate balance is between moving resources to reflect need and protecting current levels of funding to protect the stability of commissioners and providers.  It is tempting to assume in the \ncurrent context of resource constraint that setting aside the target estimates and giving all CCGs the same growth may be the fairest solution.  However, this takes no account of rapid population rises and declines that, if ignored, could drive some areas \nin to financial distress.\n114\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nI\nn setting its allocation policy NHS England has to demonstrate that the policy does not destabilise local health economies.   Initial analysis of estimates of ‘target’ allocations for CCGs appears to indicate a strong link betwee\nn ‘underfunding’ and both CCGs currently at risk of deficit and local health economies with deficit trusts.\n115\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nOf the 13 CCGs reporting a 2013\n–14\n forecast deficit in August\n 2013\n, 11 are below their ‘target’ allocations. The average distance from target of tho\nse 13 CCGS is 3.21% or £11.3\n \nm\nillion\n under target. A total of 42 providers are identified as in deficit at \nquarter \n1, 17 Foundation Trusts and 25 non-FT providers. \nThirty\n of the 42 relevant commissioning CCGs (or groups of CCGs) mapped to these providers a\nre under target allocations by an average of 2.27% or £11.8\n \nm\nillion\n.\n116\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nNHS England is currently developing and analysing the evidence base for ‘pace of change’ decisions and considering options for, and implications of, potential multi-year allocations from \n2014\n–15.\n117\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIt is proposed that resources for \np\nrimary \nc\nare, covering primary medical services (GPs), dental care, pharmaceutical services and ophthalmology services and totalling £11.1\n \nb\nillio\nn in 2013\n–14\n, should be set through separate formulae. For the \nlargest element, primary medical services, an allocation based on the Carr-Hill formula is proposed. This is largely based on need, reflecting the number of patients registered and age-gender mix of the practice, as well as factors related to the health st\natus of the population.  These factors could be regarded as a proxy for inequalities but there is no specific additional adjustment for deprivation or inequalities in the base formula which has been developed. Distinct formulae have been developed for dent\nal services, based on an age-cost curve by deprivation index for those accessing NHS dental care, and pharmaceutical services, which uses the prescribing formula used in CCG allocations as a proxy for the cost of community pharmacy services.\n118\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nCurrent NHS En\ngland strategy is to increase the proportion of funding routed through the Global Sum starting with the phasing out of MPIG\n (minimum practice income guarantee)\n. This over time will better align funding to need.\n119\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSpecialised services are nationally commissio\nned to a common standard.  Area \nT\neams have a relationship with providers in their area, rather than providing services for a specific population.  Resources are therefore determined by patient referrals (reflecting need) and constrained at national level r\nather than being subject to local allocations.\n4.2&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFinancial pressures in the system, such as funding for general practice, and for A&amp;E services.120\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe final funding that goes to \nproviders, including \ngen\neral practice and A&amp;E services\n,\n \nis \ngenerally \ndetermined \nby local commissioning arrangements via CCGs\n and \nPublic Health England (see \nc\nhart \n1\n, section \n4.1)\n.\n121\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAs part of discussions on overall funding,  analysis of pressures across the whole system are assessed by the Shared Financial Planning \nAgreement \nb\noard\n.\n122\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDifferent priorities \nneed to be funded from the resource \ngrowth \navailable \nto the NHS. \nPressures \nare grouped into three categories:\n123\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nUnit cost \npressures cover the cost of m\neeting existing commitments that are essential for delivery of NHS services. They do not cover underlying \ndemand, or increased levels of activity, which may arise due to demographic pressures or medical advance. Service developments are new areas of activi\nty which arise due to new \nstrategies, \npolic\nies \nand priorities\n.\n124\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nH\nospital and community health service (H\nCHS\n)\n pay bill pressures are the largest component of the \nunit cost \npressures and usually form the first call on NHS resources. Managing \nthese \npressures \neffectively allows the NHS to treat a growing ageing population whil\ne\n making best use of the funding available.\n125\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTable \n2\n shows how funding increases have been allocated across \nunit cost \npressures, demand and service developments in p\nrevious\n Spending Review periods.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nTable \n2\n – Disposition of Revenue Increase Across Expenditure Components\n (£ billion)\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nOutturnPlan&#xa0;\nSR2004CSR2007First 2 years of SR20102013-142014-15Activity \ng\nrowth\n2.9\n1.1\n0.8\n2.2\n1.8\nService \nd\nevelopment\n1.6\n1.7\n0.3\n0.5\n0.5\nHCHS \np\nay (\np\nrice only \nc\nomponent)\n1.7\n2\n0.2\n0.9\n0.7\nSecondary \nc\nare \nd\nrugs\n0.3\n0.4\n0.3\n0.4\n0\nOther (including central budgets)\n0.3\n0.1\n-0.1\n0.6\n-0.5\nPrimary \nc\nare \nd\nrugs\n0.3\n0.3\n-0.2\n0.4\n0.2\nGeneral \nd\nentistry, \no\nphthalmic and \np\nharmaceutical \ns\nervices\n0.2\n0.2\n0.2\n0.1\n0.1\nProcurement\n0.1\n0.1\n0.9\n0.3\n0.1\nGeneral \nm\nedical \ns\nervices\n0.1\n0.2\n0.1\n0.1\n0.2\nFunding for \ns\nocial \nc\nare\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n0.5\n0.2\n0.2\nProductivity\n-0.3\n-0.3\n-0.4\n-1.2\n-1.3\nAverage annual increase in revenue\n7.2\n5.7\n3.7\n4.2\n2.5\nNote:\nSR2004 and \nCSR2007 activity growth numbers exclude purchases of healthcare from non\n-\nNHS bodies, whereas they a\nre included in the SR\n20\n10 figures.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n126\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThere are £2.5\n \nb\nillio\nn of increased revenue resources available in 2014\n–15\n for the NHS to meet in-year pressures. This is lower than the previous three \nS\npending \nR\neview periods, lower than the first two years of th\ne 2010\n \nS\npending \nR\neview\n \nand lower than the planned disposition of resources for 2013\n–14\n.\n127\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe difficulty of allocating \nresources is therefore more acute than it has been in the previous ten years. Of the £2.5\n \nb\nillio\nn available, demand pressures consume £1.8\n \nb\nillio\nn, even after an assumption that demand growth will be lower than in recent years due to the transformational a\nctivities being undertaken as part of the NHS\n \nQIPP challenge.\n128\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAt the same time as demand is growing, the NHS must improve its services, responding to the challenge set by the Francis report into Mid Staffordshire, the Keogh Review into hospital mortality \nand the Berwick review on patient safety.  NHS England welcomes the focus on growing a culture which puts patients first, engages and empowers patients and carers, supports transparency and learning and takes responsibility for poor care. This is all under\npinned by having the right staff with the right skills and knowledge.\n129\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTherefore, i\nmprovements in workforce productivity are key to helping deliver the \nservice improvements and \nefficiency savings in this, and the next, \ns\npending \nr\nound period. So far, workfor\nce productivity gains have contributed 12\n%\n of the total savings made in 2011\n–12\n and 2012\n–13\n, compared \nwith\n 23\n%\n which has come from pay restraint. The workforce productivity share of total savings is expected to grow to 26\n% \nin 2013\n–14\n and 201\n4\n–15\n.\n130\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDespite i\nmproved productivity performance in the last two years, there still exists wide labour productivity variation at \nprovider\n \nlevel.\n \nLevelling up performance as well as shifting the average \nprovider\n performance upwards will help achieve the workforce pr\noductiv\nity gains that are need\ned.\n \nHowever, while much of this improvement can be achieved through concerted action by clinicians and managers, a substantial proportion will require transformational change in the provider land\ns\ncape to remove structural inefficienc\nies\n.\n&#xa0;\nNovember 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \nNational Audit Office (2012) \nProgress in making NHS efficiency savings\n (HC 686) \nwww.nao.org.uk/wp-\nc\nontent/uploads/2012/12/1213686.pdf\n&#xa0;\n \n \nDepartment of Health (2013) \nBetter Procurement, Better Value, Better Care: A Procurement Development Programme for the NHS\n \nwww.gov.uk/government/uploads/s\ny\nstem/uploads/attachment_data/file/226835/procurement_development_programme_for_NHS.pdf\n&#xa0;\n NHS England (2013) \nThe NHS belongs to the people: \na\n call to action\nwww.england.nhs.uk/\n2\n013/07/11/call-to-action/\n HM Treasury (December 2012) \nA new approach to public private partnerships\nwww.gov.u\nk\n/government\n/\nuploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/205112/pf2_infrastructure_new_approach_to_public_private_parnerships_051212.pdf\n Department of Health (2013) \nIntegrated Care and Support: Our S\nhared Commitment\n \nwww.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachmen\nt_data/file/198748/DEFINITIVE_FINAL_VERSION_Integrated_Care_and_Support_-_Our_Shared_Commitment_2013-05-13.pdf\n"